<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910219-0005</DOCNO><DOCID>910219-0005.</DOCID><HL>   Four Concerns to Support   Fiber-Optic Specifications</HL><DATE>02/19/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   T J.FUT HIT DD BTY</CO><IN>COMMUNICATIONS TECHNOLOGY (CMT)</IN><LP>   TOKYO -- Four of the world's leading telecommunicationscompanies said they have agreed to make compatiblefiber-optic products, a move that should facilitate thespread of such equipment.   American Telephone andamp; Telegraph Co., Fujitsu Ltd., HitachiLtd., and BTandamp;D Technologies -- a joint venture betweenBritish Telecom PLC and Du Pont Co. -- announced yesterdaythat they would support common specifications within analready existing international standard called Sonet, orSynchronous Optical Network.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;We expect that this multiple sourcing agreement willdramatically accelerate the evolution of a world-standardlightwave network toward the 21st century,&quot; Hiroki Yoshine, aHitachi official, said in a press release.   Analysts last year predicted that Sonet business willreach $250 million in 1994 and $1 billion by 1997.</TEXT></DOC>